<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<p>In any dense system, the positional and BO orders are coupled with each other, so for a complete description of the structure, one has to consider both of them. The most natural way for such a description is provided by the pair distribution function (PDF) [
 <xref rid="B1-materials-12-03464" ref-type="bibr">1</xref>,
 <xref rid="B74-materials-12-03464" ref-type="bibr">74</xref>], which in homogeneous systems can be determined as Equation (19):
 <disp-formula id="FD20-materials-12-03464">
  <label>(19)</label>
  <math id="mm177">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <mi>g</mi>
     <mrow>
      <mo>(</mo>
      <mi mathvariant="bold-italic">r</mi>
      <mo>)</mo>
     </mrow>
     <mo>=</mo>
     <mfrac>
      <mn>1</mn>
      <mrow>
       <msup>
        <mrow>
         <mo stretchy="false">〈</mo>
         <mi>n</mi>
         <mo stretchy="false">〉</mo>
        </mrow>
        <mn>2</mn>
       </msup>
       <mi>V</mi>
      </mrow>
     </mfrac>
     <mo stretchy="false">〈</mo>
     <munder>
      <mstyle mathsize="140%" displaystyle="true">
       <mo>∑</mo>
      </mstyle>
      <mrow>
       <mi>i</mi>
       <mo>≠</mo>
       <mi>j</mi>
      </mrow>
     </munder>
     <mi>δ</mi>
     <mrow>
      <mo>(</mo>
      <mrow>
       <mi mathvariant="bold-italic">r</mi>
       <mo>−</mo>
       <msub>
        <mi mathvariant="bold-italic">r</mi>
        <mi>i</mi>
       </msub>
       <mo>+</mo>
       <msub>
        <mi mathvariant="bold-italic">r</mi>
        <mi>j</mi>
       </msub>
      </mrow>
      <mo>)</mo>
      <mo stretchy="false">〉</mo>
     </mrow>
     <mo>,</mo>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </disp-formula> where 〈
 <italic>n</italic>〉 is an average density of particles, 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm179">
   <mrow>
    <mi>V</mi>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> is a volume of the system, angular brackets 〈…〉 denote ensemble averaging, the indexes 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm181">
   <mrow>
    <mi>i</mi>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> and 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm182">
   <mrow>
    <mi>j</mi>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> enumerate all particles in the system, and 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm183">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <msub>
      <mi mathvariant="bold-italic">r</mi>
      <mi>i</mi>
     </msub>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> is the position of the 
 <italic>i</italic>-th particle. The PDF 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm184">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <mi>g</mi>
     <mrow>
      <mo>(</mo>
      <mi mathvariant="bold-italic">r</mi>
      <mo>)</mo>
     </mrow>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> defines the probability of finding a particle at the separation 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm185">
   <mrow>
    <mi mathvariant="bold-italic">r</mi>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> from any other arbitrarily chosen particle. Usually for isotropic systems, e.g., simple liquids, due to ensemble averaging in Equation (19) the angular dependence of 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm186">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <mi>g</mi>
     <mrow>
      <mo>(</mo>
      <mi mathvariant="bold-italic">r</mi>
      <mo>)</mo>
     </mrow>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> washes out, so one considers the so-called radial distribution function 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm187">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <mi>g</mi>
     <mrow>
      <mo>(</mo>
      <mi mathvariant="bold-italic">r</mi>
      <mo>)</mo>
     </mrow>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>, which is the PDF 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm188">
   <mrow>
    <mrow>
     <mi>g</mi>
     <mrow>
      <mo>(</mo>
      <mi mathvariant="bold-italic">r</mi>
      <mo>)</mo>
     </mrow>
    </mrow>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> averaged over all possible directions of the vector 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="mm189">
   <mrow>
    <mi mathvariant="bold-italic">r</mi>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>. However, in the case of a system exhibiting the BO order, such angular averaging will lead to the loss of structural information. Thus, below we will consider non-averaged angular-dependent PDF.
</p>
